WEBVTT

00:15.618 --> 00:22.265
and welcome to the Petty Profit Podcast, where we talk about news, culture, and politics from a Christian worldview.

00:22.506 --> 00:32.517
And today is a little different because I had a kind of my typical Tuesday essay that I was working on for today.

00:32.577 --> 00:34.779
And I just need a little more time on it.

00:35.080 --> 00:38.503
So hope to have that for you next week.

00:39.224 --> 00:44.370
But I didn't want to leave you down and leave you empty-handed here on a Tuesday.

00:44.770 --> 00:48.776
And so here I am, no script, no plan.

00:49.397 --> 00:53.062
You get to hear me in all my inarticulate glory here.

00:53.202 --> 00:59.851
So before we figure that out, I just want to ask you, you the listener, how are you doing?

01:00.332 --> 01:01.794
I hope things are going well.

01:02.155 --> 01:06.221
I'm curious about the people who are listening to this show.

01:06.241 --> 01:12.850
A few of you write in on a semi-regular basis and I get to hear from you, which is really cool.

01:12.962 --> 01:14.224
But a lot of you don't.

01:14.284 --> 01:19.652
So I, you know, I have no idea who you are, what your story is, how you found the show.

01:19.712 --> 01:22.196
And I would love to hear from you.

01:22.397 --> 01:22.998
I really would.

01:23.478 --> 01:34.055
You know, so if you're interested in reaching out, you can always email me at, it's the email address is contact at thepetitprofit.com.

01:34.215 --> 01:36.478
So it's contact at thepetitprofit.com.

01:37.620 --> 01:41.426
If you have a question, a fun story to tell,

01:41.634 --> 01:46.219
you know, an idea for, you know, maybe subject matter on an upcoming podcast.

01:46.279 --> 01:46.980
Send it on to me.

01:47.000 --> 01:48.682
I'd love to hear from you.

01:48.742 --> 01:50.243
I'd love to learn more about you.

01:50.283 --> 01:52.566
Either way, I just appreciate you reaching out.

01:52.586 --> 01:56.030
And it's good to know there are people out there that are listening and love the show.

01:56.130 --> 01:59.874
So, gosh, what to do?

01:59.954 --> 02:00.475
What to do?

02:01.035 --> 02:07.262
I'm here on the main homepage of discern.com.

02:07.703 --> 02:09.324
And you may know about discern.

02:09.384 --> 02:10.866
If you don't, you should.

02:10.946 --> 02:17.016
It's a, you know, I used to be a big fan of the judge report.

02:17.036 --> 02:21.544
It's kind of where I logged in every morning to get my news.

02:21.864 --> 02:26.211
It was a pretty good aggregator of all the interesting news stories out there.

02:26.271 --> 02:30.258
And something happened somewhere along the line, I think last year.

02:30.562 --> 02:34.227
Something changed, whether it changed hands or changed ownership.

02:34.828 --> 02:37.532
The material just wasn't the same as it used to be.

02:37.872 --> 02:40.215
And about that same time the CERN came along.

02:40.235 --> 02:46.043
And it's run by Adam Ford, who you may know was the founder of the Babylon Bee, really good guy.

02:46.103 --> 02:59.922
And he's built this really, really incredible website, really for politically minded Christians, you know, for people like us who want to see the most important news stories of the day.

03:00.386 --> 03:01.848
He finds the good stuff.

03:01.868 --> 03:03.110
He finds the interesting stuff.

03:03.130 --> 03:05.775
So I encourage you to check it out if you haven't.

03:05.795 --> 03:06.956
It's at discern.com.

03:06.976 --> 03:08.298
It's d-i-s-r-n.

03:08.599 --> 03:11.423
So it's missing a few letters.

03:12.365 --> 03:17.513
That's fashionable these days to take a couple letters out of a name.

03:18.635 --> 03:20.938
But it's d-i-s-r-n.com.

03:21.079 --> 03:22.841
So I'm here on the home page.

03:22.922 --> 03:25.746
Let's see what's on the home page today.

03:27.106 --> 03:27.607
Oh, let's see.

03:27.647 --> 03:27.887
Okay.

03:28.007 --> 03:31.752
Oh, Washington Redskins officially announced their name change.

03:31.812 --> 03:34.255
So that's gosh.

03:35.937 --> 03:56.562
I remember talking about this all the way back in college, you know, back in, you know, 2007, the college I went to required at least one ethnic studies course to graduate, which was, you know, essentially a course on leftist ideology and Marxism with this,

03:57.090 --> 04:00.715
ethnic studies stamp put on it.

04:00.815 --> 04:10.429
But yeah, I remember way back then they were talking about how they needed to change the name of the Washington Redskins and shoot.

04:10.449 --> 04:12.292
Here we are 13 years later.

04:12.332 --> 04:16.158
It looks like they're finally doing it because of everything that's going on right now.

04:16.278 --> 04:19.122
So it looks like their statement

04:19.554 --> 04:24.481
Let's see their statement was sent out today from the Washington Redskins football team.

04:24.541 --> 04:29.448
It says this on July 3rd, we announced the commencement of a thorough review of the team's name.

04:29.508 --> 04:32.312
That review has begun in earnest as part of this process.

04:32.332 --> 04:36.418
We want to keep our sponsors fans and community apprised of our thinking as we go forward.

04:37.199 --> 04:44.309
Today we are announcing we will be retiring the Redskins name and logo upon completion of this review.

04:45.310 --> 04:46.051
So there you go.

04:46.852 --> 04:48.274
It's gone.

04:48.930 --> 04:50.992
Yeah, looking at some comments here.

04:51.012 --> 04:52.094
Yeah, just a matter of time.

04:52.734 --> 04:54.216
Yeah, I guess no surprise.

04:57.159 --> 05:08.713
I don't know what this is going to do to help anybody to help any real actual living human beings to make their lives better.

05:08.973 --> 05:09.754
You know, I don't know.

05:09.994 --> 05:15.180
But, you know, we love these symbolic gestures, don't we?

05:15.300 --> 05:16.882
You know, it's easy to

05:17.218 --> 05:28.115
to do a symbolic gesture, a lot easier to do that than to actually look at the problem with a shred of honesty and try to solve it with a shred of resolve.

05:28.195 --> 05:30.158
So there you have it.

05:30.899 --> 05:33.644
We'll see what their, we see what name they come up with.

05:34.565 --> 05:42.558
The Babylon Bee did a great article, a name change suggestion for the Washington Redskins.

05:43.479 --> 05:45.362
Since they're in the city of

05:45.538 --> 05:57.172
Washington, D.C., you know, the city of politics and corruption, they recommended renaming the team to the Washington Wizard people, which I think is a great name.

05:57.293 --> 06:00.176
They should consider Washington Wizard people.

06:00.276 --> 06:06.604
That would be a much more fitting name, I think, for the population of Washington, D.C.

06:06.684 --> 06:07.946
So that's that story.

06:07.986 --> 06:08.927
Let's see what else we got.

06:10.769 --> 06:14.514
New York City reports zero coronavirus deaths.

06:14.594 --> 06:16.296
for first time since pandemic began.

06:16.376 --> 06:17.097
Wow, that's okay.

06:17.117 --> 06:17.778
That's good news.

06:18.079 --> 06:18.659
Excellent news.

06:20.422 --> 06:25.909
Kind of ironic and strange since we're all, you know, we're kind of jumping back into this lockdown craze everywhere.

06:26.510 --> 06:27.030
But here we are.

06:27.050 --> 06:30.916
No coronavirus deaths in New York City.

06:31.016 --> 06:31.657
Good news there.

06:33.239 --> 06:38.866
Meanwhile in California, California has completely locked down once again.

06:39.522 --> 06:48.556
Governor Newsom orders statewide re-closure of all indoor dining, as well as church services and hair salons.

06:49.317 --> 06:55.146
You know, basically all the small businesses that keep the economy afloat, those are gone.

06:55.807 --> 07:02.177
His winery, Gavin Newsom's personal winery, of course, will remain open.

07:02.878 --> 07:04.019
Of course, that's important.

07:04.300 --> 07:04.921
It's important.

07:05.542 --> 07:08.306
You know, with the masks and all that,

07:09.410 --> 07:12.094
It's still such a point of contention.

07:12.815 --> 07:35.331
Even among people on the same side of the political aisle, even among conservatives or even among Christians, I posted something to Facebook today because our home city, our city council voted today on a measure to require the wearing of masks in all public places.

07:35.411 --> 07:37.554
And so I had posted

07:38.434 --> 07:51.006
the emails of City Council so that people could reach out to them and voice their opinion on our local city requiring masks.

07:51.046 --> 07:53.369
And it seems like a lot of local cities have done that.

07:54.530 --> 07:54.850
I don't know.

07:54.890 --> 07:58.414
I don't want to debate it necessarily.

07:58.454 --> 08:05.661
I think people on both sides can disagree in good faith on whether masks work, whether they don't.

08:05.761 --> 08:06.802
I think that there's

08:07.106 --> 08:14.254
You know, sound scientific arguments on either side that would suggest that masks work and also that they don't work.

08:15.255 --> 08:21.262
You know, it is hard to know what to believe these days with, you know, just the abundance of information out there.

08:21.342 --> 08:29.611
But, you know, for me, I was talking with my wife about this when we were traveling a couple of weeks ago, we were at the airport and everyone was wearing a mask.

08:29.631 --> 08:31.313
You know, of course they require them on a plane.

08:31.353 --> 08:33.795
So I wore the mask on the plane and that was it.

08:34.936 --> 08:36.338
I didn't wear it in

08:36.546 --> 08:37.547
any of the airports.

08:38.188 --> 08:39.489
And I stuck out like a sore thumb.

08:39.729 --> 08:44.875
I looked at everyone, you know, I got dirty looks, you know, I've already had the virus.

08:44.895 --> 08:46.576
So I knew I wasn't infecting anybody.

08:46.636 --> 09:03.794
But I, this might seem a little melodramatic, but I feel like I need to practice being willing to stand out and being willing to be an outcast, I guess.

09:04.002 --> 09:09.529
Even if it's something trivial as a mask, I don't feel they help.

09:10.190 --> 09:20.063
I know personally that I don't need to wear one to protect anybody because I've already had the virus, so I felt like wearing one was a lie.

09:20.163 --> 09:25.170
It was like a lie to make other people feel better, and that just didn't sit well with me.

09:25.442 --> 09:26.864
I didn't wear one at the airport.

09:27.285 --> 09:29.628
It drove my wife crazy because she wore one.

09:29.668 --> 09:33.794
She wears one and, you know, she's, she's a lot nicer than me and she follows rules.

09:34.335 --> 09:38.981
And, uh, but, you know, I don't know.

09:39.121 --> 09:53.682
I, I think that, you know, that while the mask issue might be kind of trivial and it's a small minor inconvenience, I don't like the idea that so many people are so, um,

09:54.178 --> 10:02.268
seem to be so unquestionably obedient and just are willing to accept what experts say.

10:02.608 --> 10:07.314
I'm way more skeptical of experts.

10:07.734 --> 10:12.620
And I want to practice standing out and standing up.

10:13.661 --> 10:24.114
If for some reason, you know, one, two, three years, 10 years down the road, we are asked or pressured into doing something different, something worse.

10:24.610 --> 10:30.176
And I figure I might as well practice being a bit disagreeable.

10:31.057 --> 10:33.760
So that's my reasoning behind it.

10:33.820 --> 10:37.884
I don't know if that is good reasoning or not, but that's my reasoning.

10:40.627 --> 10:41.929
Let's see what else we got.

10:43.891 --> 10:49.797
LA and San Diego Public Schools will be online only for the remainder of this year.

10:49.837 --> 10:52.720
So the kids in California are not going back to school.

10:52.780 --> 10:54.482
That is great news.

10:55.682 --> 10:57.424
Great news for the kids of California.

10:58.125 --> 11:00.389
The longer they stay home from those schools, the better.

11:03.673 --> 11:09.541
At least for the kids that are in good home situations, for the kids that aren't, God help us.

11:09.922 --> 11:14.628
And I pray for their protection and their safety.

11:17.232 --> 11:18.834
Let's see what else we got here.

11:19.330 --> 11:24.016
Again, in Chicago, this is almost sounding like old news at this point.

11:24.076 --> 11:28.181
64 people were shot, 13 people were killed in Chicago over the weekend.

11:28.201 --> 11:32.486
It just never ends.

11:34.208 --> 11:41.377
There was this thing that happened, I think, when Black Lives Matter initially kicked off after the George Floyd killing.

11:42.338 --> 11:45.202
I think a lot of well-meaning people took that

11:45.538 --> 12:14.514
phrase black lives matter they and they took it literally they said oh yeah okay black lives matter you know let's let's let's save black lives and you know oh let's we need to talk about gang violence we need to talk about you know all these people that are getting shot in chicago in new york city and and they were quickly shouted down oh no no no no no wait wait wait no no that's that's um we're not talking about those those black lives you know black lives matter is is a cause only for black people who are killed by police that's why we're

12:14.594 --> 12:15.075
marching.

12:15.415 --> 12:19.039
You know, the other Black lives, yeah, that's, that's a different, different cause.

12:19.239 --> 12:22.103
We don't care.

12:23.424 --> 12:31.013
But it's, it's so sad to just see this, just this constant tragedy play out every single week and every single weekend.

12:31.053 --> 12:32.074
Nobody seems to care.

12:32.114 --> 12:33.496
No one's doing anything about it.

12:34.017 --> 12:38.642
The only people that are doing something are pulling funding away from the cops.

12:38.818 --> 12:44.665
in a time when violence is skyrocketing and kids are being killed, a one year old was shot at a barbecue last week.

12:46.467 --> 12:54.957
A little black kid, one year old shot, who knows, some altercation or to gain violence or who knows what.

12:56.118 --> 13:00.303
And these people are talking about defunding the police in this climate.

13:00.343 --> 13:06.290
It's just, you know, I'm very skeptical of their claim that they actually care about black lives.

13:06.946 --> 13:10.450
You know, I think they care about their politics and they're using black lives.

13:11.571 --> 13:13.233
But I don't think they care about black lives.

13:15.135 --> 13:15.535
Let's see.

13:15.555 --> 13:15.916
What else?

13:16.036 --> 13:16.376
One more.

13:16.396 --> 13:16.997
One more.

13:17.037 --> 13:18.719
And then we'll be done here.

13:18.739 --> 13:27.849
Oh, Idaho Congressman calls for removal of Margaret Sanger bust from the National Portrait Gallery.

13:27.869 --> 13:28.590
That's a good idea.

13:30.211 --> 13:36.338
So yeah, Margaret Sanger was the white supremacist eugenicist.

13:36.802 --> 13:40.506
Who founded Planned Parenthood along with a bunch of other eugenicists?

13:41.768 --> 13:43.429
And her statue is still standing.

13:43.489 --> 13:47.734
So while we're removing statues, we should probably add her to the mix as well.

13:49.416 --> 13:49.796
You know what?

13:49.837 --> 13:50.998
Let's do a couple more here.

13:51.018 --> 13:52.019
There's a lot of good stuff here.

13:53.160 --> 13:54.181
What's this?

13:56.023 --> 14:01.810
Decorated 12 tour veteran dubbed Captain America dies by suicide.

14:03.612 --> 14:05.554
Master Sergeant Andrew Christian.

14:06.114 --> 14:15.466
Mark and Sano, a decorated green beret, a silver star recipient, 12 tour veteran whose friends called him the real Captain America, died by suicide on July 6th.

14:15.526 --> 14:17.649
He had a wife and three small children gosh dang.

14:23.056 --> 14:30.345
I don't know how this man was able to surf 12 tours overseas.

14:31.126 --> 14:34.450
Anyone who is serving

14:35.362 --> 14:36.143
12 tours.

14:37.024 --> 14:38.005
That's not healthy.

14:38.466 --> 14:40.047
There's something wrong.

14:42.250 --> 14:45.073
How he was allowed to do this, I can't even imagine.

14:46.295 --> 14:47.036
I can't imagine.

14:47.837 --> 14:48.337
My gosh.

14:49.318 --> 14:53.083
Six tours in Afghanistan and six tours with the Ranger Regiment.

14:56.306 --> 15:00.291
He is the 30th member of his battalion to commit suicide.

15:00.331 --> 15:02.834
This is a big deal.

15:03.042 --> 15:17.677
You know, this is home for me too, because I only did one tour in Iraq as a Marine Corps infantryman and a handful of my friends have killed themselves since coming back as well.

15:18.978 --> 15:23.183
It's a real epidemic.

15:23.243 --> 15:24.864
It's a whole mix of things, I think.

15:25.185 --> 15:30.290
There's this never-ending war that we've been involved in for

15:30.818 --> 15:33.001
over a decade now, well over a decade.

15:33.683 --> 15:41.174
I think there's been an exit of Christianity, meaning and purpose from our culture.

15:41.315 --> 15:53.714
And then, you know, on top of that, military psychiatrists are over-medicating, way over-medicating, people who are having psychological difficulties and

15:54.338 --> 15:55.760
You know, I've seen the effects of it.

15:56.041 --> 16:01.348
I know, personally, know people who've experienced the effects of it, and it's a real shame.

16:01.409 --> 16:05.114
So, you know, keep the military in your prayers right now.

16:05.194 --> 16:13.166
You know, it's something that's kind of a little bit been out of sight, out of mind, with all of the other stuff going on.

16:13.667 --> 16:17.713
But suicide is a terrible crisis in the military right now.

16:18.053 --> 16:21.138
And I think there's a bit of

16:21.538 --> 16:28.965
poison in the culture, and there's this overabundance of medication, and people just need the Lord.

16:29.045 --> 16:31.387
We need to pray for folks who are struggling.

16:31.447 --> 16:47.763
I don't know how I came back as mentally sound as I did, and I sensed it while I was over there, almost a sense that God almost kind of had a shield around my mind or my spirit while I was over there.

16:47.803 --> 16:51.346
It sounds weird to say, but I'm really grateful

16:51.522 --> 17:05.797
I'm grateful that God protected me while I was serving and a lot of people I served with and a lot of people I am close to can't say the same thing.

17:06.999 --> 17:21.074
So be praying for our men and women in the military who are still serving tours over there and still facing this struggle every day.

17:22.306 --> 17:25.309
So much bad news in the world.

17:26.190 --> 17:30.154
So much brokenness and hopelessness, anger, rage.

17:30.855 --> 17:33.958
You do get the sense that things are toppling.

17:34.238 --> 17:36.921
Everything's kind of crumbling and falling apart.

17:37.381 --> 17:39.403
I don't know if they are or if they aren't.

17:40.284 --> 17:45.890
That's not for me to say, but all I can say is that, hey, Christian, it's time for us to get to work.

17:46.590 --> 17:50.194
Whatever God is calling you to do, double down on it, start it,

17:50.434 --> 17:56.542
Reach out to that person, reach out to that neighbor, have that discussion, serve that person.

17:57.523 --> 17:58.705
We have a lot of work to do.

17:59.065 --> 18:05.954
Not to save the culture or the country or to turn things around the way we want them to be.

18:05.994 --> 18:12.402
The world is going to go, the way the world is going to go, but we are here to introduce

18:12.834 --> 18:16.479
people to the one who saved us and the one who died for us.

18:16.579 --> 18:25.651
And so, you know, in the midst of all this brokenness and confusion, the fields, you know, as Jesus said, are white for the harvest.

18:26.152 --> 18:31.819
And there are a lot of people and more every day who need to hear this stuff.

18:32.180 --> 18:42.834
So, you know, it seems like everything I just read, everything I went through, it's just one call after another for we as Christians to be engaged

18:42.946 --> 18:53.157
You know, not just online, not just in media, but face to face with our friends, with our family, with the person down the street.

18:53.778 --> 18:56.120
So ask God what that might look like for you.

18:56.160 --> 18:57.782
It's going to look different for each one of us.

18:58.223 --> 18:59.905
We're each gifted differently.

19:00.405 --> 19:06.652
We're each placed differently and in each job, each person's job is going to look a little bit different.

19:06.692 --> 19:08.594
So anyway,

19:08.674 --> 19:13.640
Um, yeah, that was my, this is, this has been my off the cuff episode.

19:13.680 --> 19:27.856
Sorry that it wasn't as, uh, as prim and polished and produced as, uh, I typically like it to be, but, um, uh, but you guys are, are really great listeners, really great audience.

19:27.876 --> 19:32.882
And, uh, I want to make sure that, uh, that I have something out for you.

19:33.322 --> 19:34.944
Um, I appreciate the chance to do that.

19:35.144 --> 19:36.626
And, uh, I would love to hear from you.

19:37.058 --> 19:40.962
Again, if you want to reach out to the show, it's contact at thepetitprofit.com.

19:41.603 --> 19:49.172
Contact at thepetitprofit.com or you can visit the website and there's a contact form on there if you want to reach out.

19:49.372 --> 19:50.934
So thanks for listening.

19:51.715 --> 19:52.616
I love you guys.

19:52.636 --> 19:53.897
I love each one of you.

19:54.318 --> 19:56.981
I appreciate all your support.

19:57.782 --> 20:05.170
And I am praying for you just as you navigate the craziness of this life and the difficulties.

20:05.442 --> 20:16.280
that God will use you and that His Spirit will fill you and enable you to complete this mission that we're all here for.

20:16.461 --> 20:27.439
So we will talk to you later this Thursday with another man hug and I will have this nice little produced essay for you next Tuesday.

20:27.820 --> 20:28.761
So thank you very much.

20:28.821 --> 20:31.666
This has been the Petty Prophet podcast.

